column1: #Text=Image : ВО Свобода .
#Text=A Crimean self-defense group with shields painted as the flag of the autonomous republic .
#Text=Image : E. Arrott .
#Text=Wednesday , March 5 , 2014

#Text=In the past few days , tension has been increasing due to conflict between Ukraine and the Russian Federation which has led to the United States , the United Kingdom , and France increasing pressure on Russia to remove their troops from Crimea .

#Text=Wikinews interviewed specialists in Russian foreign policy and specialists in international law about the legality of Russia 's actions and the consequences of any sanctions imposed by G7 nation economies .
#Text=Interviewees
#Text=Wikinews interviewed :
#Text=Jane Burbank , Professor of History and Russian and Slavic Studies at the New York University , New York
#Text=Jeremy Morris , Senior Lecturer in Russian Studies at the University of Birmingham , Birmingham
#Text=Craig Brandist , Professor of Cultural Theory and Intellectual History in the Department of Russian and Slavonic Studies at the University of Sheffield , Sheffield
#Text=Stephen Blank , Senior Fellow for Russia at the American Foreign Policy Council in Washington , D.C.
#Text=Yanni Kotsonis , Director , New York University Jordan Center for the Advanced Study of Russia in New York .
#Text=Wikinews Q&A
#Text=File photo of interviewee Craig Brandist .
#Text=Image : Craig Brandist .
#Text=( ( Wikinews ) ) Are Russian troop deployments into Ukrainian territory a clear violation of sovereignty ?
#Text=Morris : Yes .
#Text=Burbank : Yes , the borders of the Ukrainian state were drawn up in 1991 and reinforced by the 1994 Budapest accords .
#Text=See the article by Paul Goble on these accords .
#Text=Brandist : It would be hard to describe it otherwise .
#Text=That said , however , it is quite extraordinary hypocrisy for the US and UK to strike moral poses about this , especially after Iraq and Afghanistan .

#Text=Russia clearly has strategic interests in the region , and there is a large Russian-speaking population in much of Ukraine , a majority in Crimea and an important part of the east of the country , and the arrangement after the collapse of the USSR was clearly fragile , especially when NATO expansion took place .
#Text=None of this is to excuse Russian actions , but they cannot be understood without focus on the ' great game ' of which it is part .

#Text=Blank : By any standard Russia 's actions represent a violation of Ukrainian sovereignty and integrity , a premeditated break with numerous treaties signed by Russia guaranteeing Ukraine 's security , integrity , and sovereignty , and thus Premier Yatsenyuk is right these are acts of war .
#Text=Kotsonis : On the surface it seems so .
#Text=Mind you , it is complicated because Russia has been given rights to the bases on the Crimea and this may give Russia the pretext for a larger intervention .

#Text=But it does not seem to be a clear-cut legal case for intervention and everyone understands that this is Russia smarting over the loss of an ally in Yanukovich and guarding its own back yard interests .
